,"1190":"1190","1224":"1224","1189":"1189","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","Abt 1224":"circa 1224","1162":"1162","about 1165":"circa 1165","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","of Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk",",,, England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1165–":"about 1165–Deceased","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1170–Female":"1170–Deceased","1172–Female":"1172–Deceased","1189–Female":"1189–Deceased","1190–1242":"1190–1242","1224–Female":"1224–Deceased","1160–Male":"1160–Deceased","1162–Female":"1162–Deceased","1190":"1190","1224":"1224","1189":"1189","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","Abt 1224":"about 1224","1162":"1162","about 1165":"about 1165","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","of Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom",",,, England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bassingham","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk): habitational name from Great and Little Massingham (Norfolk). The placenames derive from the Old English personal name <i>Mæssa</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i> (genitive <i>-inga-</i>) + <i>hām</i> ‘village, homestead’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Bassingham was born about 1165, in England, United Kingdom, her father, Piers De Bassingham, was 7 and her mother, Mrs Piers de Bassingham, was 5. She had at least 1 daughter with John De Flegg. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1165–":"umbes 1165–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","1172–Female":"1172–Surnud","1189–Female":"1189–Surnud","1190–1242":"1190–1242","1224–Female":"1224–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1162–Female":"1162–Surnud","1190":"1190","1224":"1224","1189":"1189","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","Abt 1224":"umbes 1224","1162":"1162","about 1165":"umbes 1165","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","of Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom",",,, England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1165–":"noin 1165–Kuollut","1165–Female":"1165–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","1172–Female":"1172–Kuollut","1189–Female":"1189–Kuollut","1190–1242":"1190–1242","1224–Female":"1224–Kuollut","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1162–Female":"1162–Kuollut","1190":"1190","1224":"1224","1189":"1189","1242":"1242","1165":"1165","Abt 1224":"noin 1224","1162":"1162","about 1165":"noin 1165","1172":"1172","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","of Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta",",,, England, United Kingdom":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1165–":"environ 1165–Décédée","1165–Female":"1165–Décédée","1170–Female":"1170–Décédée","1172–Female":"1172–Décédée","1189–Female":"1189–Décédée","1190–1242":"1190–1242","1224–Female":"1224–Décédée","1160–Male":"1160–Décédé","1162–Female":"1162–Décédée","1190":"1190","1224":"1224